'''Hamza Sultan Ali'''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/995119.html| title= Hamza Sultan Ali| publisher=ESPNcricinfo| access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="BP">{{cite news| url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Bristol-s-promising-cricketer-Hamza-Shabbir-dies/story-29380801-detail/story.html| title=Bristol's most promising cricketer Hamza Shabbir dies in River Avon tragedy| last=Cook| first=Tristan| work=[[Bristol Post]]| date=9 June 2016| access-date=9 June 2016| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610185328/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Bristol-s-promising-cricketer-Hamza-Shabbir-dies/story-29380801-detail/story.html| archivedate=10 June 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref> (8 August 1995 – 9 June 2016), also known as '''Hamza Shabbir''',<ref name="ES"/> was an English [[cricket]]er who played for [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]], [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Young Cricketers and [[Rawalpindi Rams]]. Primarily a right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]] bowler, he also [[Batting (cricket)|batted]] right handed. Ali attended [[City Academy Bristol]] and [[Filton]] Sixth Form College.<ref name="ES"/><ref>{{cite web|url= https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/1883/1883933/1883933.html| title=Hamza Ali|publisher=CricketArchive| access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref>
==Career== Ali played for many years for [[Stapleton, Bristol|Stapleton]] Cricket Club in the West Of England League Bristol and North Somerset Division; his step father also played for the club.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.club-cricket.co.uk/news/details/727| title= Hamza Shabbir: Young Asian took club route to county status| work=Club Cricket| date=10 June 2016| access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> In 2016, he represented [[Downend, South Gloucestershire|Downend]] Cricket Club,<ref name="BP"/><ref name="Samaa">{{cite news|url= http://www.samaa.tv/sports/2016/06/pakistan-origin-cricketer-dies-in-england-river-tragedy/| title= Pakistan-origin cricketer dies in England river tragedy| work=[[Samaa TV]]| date=9 June 2016| access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> where he was known as one of the fastest bowlers in the Bristol leagues.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.jaagtv.com/Pakistan-origin-cricketer-dies-in-England-river-tragedy-news-36501.html| title= Pakistan-origin cricketer dies in England river tragedy| work=[[Jaag TV]]| date=9 June 2016| access-date=10 June 2016}}</ref> During 2015, Ali also represented Omar Associates in the Patron's Trophy Grade II.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thenews.com.pk/print/27531-aamir-in-action-from-9th| title= Aamir in action from 9th| work=[[The News International]]| date=5 March 2015| access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> He made his [[List A cricket|List A]] debut in 2014/15 for [[Rawalpindi Rams]] against [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|National Bank of Pakistan]]; Ali took 4/39 from 8.3 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/770/770914.html| title= National Bank of Pakistan v Rawalpindi Rams| publisher=CricketArchive|access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> In the [[2015 English cricket season|2015 season]], Ali made two appearances for [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] Second XI, and he made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut in April 2016 in a pre-season match for Hampshire against [[Cardiff MCC University|Cardiff MCCU]], taking 2/47.<ref name="Cricinfo">{{cite news|url= http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2016/content/story/1024401.html| title= Hampshire cricketer Hamza Ali dies aged 20| work=[[ESPNcricinfo]]| date=9 June 2016| access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref> Ali also represented the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) Young Cricketers, with his last appearance for them being in a Second XI Championship match against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex Second XI]]; Ali scored 44 and took 4/39 in the first innings of the match.<ref name="Cricinfo"/><ref name="BBC"/>
==Death and tributes== On 9 June 2016, Ali died at around 1720 [[British Standard Time]] after drowning in the [[River Avon (Bristol)|River Avon]] near [[Saltford Lock]] to the south-east of [[Bristol]].<ref name="ES">{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/hamza-ali-tributes-paid-to-hampshire-cricketer-after-death-at-age-of-20-a3267356.html |title=Hamza Ali: Tributes to Hampshire cricketer after death at age of 20 |publisher=The Evening Standard |date=9 June 2016 |accessdate=9 June 2016 }}</ref><ref name="BBC">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/36488232 |title=Hamza Ali: Tributes after fast bowler dies, aged 20 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 June 2016 |accessdate=9 June 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://tribune.com.pk/story/1119977/20-year-old-fast-bowler-hamza-ali-passes-away/| title= 20-year-old fast bowler Hamza Ali passes away| work=[[The Express Tribune]]| date=10 June 2016| access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> He was 20 years old.<ref name="ES"/><ref name="BBC"/> Hampshire's Head of Player Development said of Ali that "He was an incredibly committed and enthusiastic cricketer who always gave 100% for the team that he was playing for", whilst MCC head coach [[Steven Kirby]] said that "He greatly impressed us with his energy, enthusiasm and exceptional all-round talent."<ref name="Cricinfo"/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/80479/hampshire-cricketer-hamza-ali-dies-aged-20| title= Hampshire cricketer Hamza Ali dies aged 20| work=[[Cricbuzz]]| date=9 June 2016| access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> In memory of Ali, Hampshire wore [[black armband]]s for their [[2016 NatWest t20 Blast|2016 T20 Blast]] match on 9 June against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]],<ref name="Cricinfo"/><ref name="BBC"/> Downend players wore black armbands on their match on 11 June, and the flags at Stapleton Cricket Club were lowered to [[half-mast]] on 9 June.<ref name="Samaa"/>
